title: List of Civil Lawsuits/Criminal Lawsuits Bought Against  Buffalo Police Officers of PD

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

copies of reports, lists, databases, or individual documents that details civil and/or criminal lawsuits of police misconduct brought against the city's police officers and/or the department by civilians or protesters who were injured during the 2020 George Floyd Protests from May 2020 to December 2021.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brianna Knibbs

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Reports/After Action Review Boston Police
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

reports or after action review that specifically indicates of how Boston Police Officers policed the 2020 George Floyd Protests.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brianna Knibbs

title: CIA: Richard Nixon's March 1991 Tbilisi visit

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: CIA: Richard Nixon's March 1991 Tbilisi visit
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

This is a request for documents or photographs related to the one-day visit of Richard Nixon to the city of Tbilisi on March 31st of 1991. While this visit is discussed in the country of Georgia, there appears to be little to no information about the visit. 

Please include the following in this request:

All photographs or photographic negatives in the agency's possession of Nixon's visit that day. Nixon traveled to polling places and met with Zviad Gamsakhurdia and other prominent Georgians. 

Any correspondence between Richard Nixon and the following CIA officials (Director William Webster, Deputy Richard James Kerr or Robert Gates) where the topic of the correspondence was either the planning for the Tbilisi visit or discussions of impressions or ramifications  of the visit. 

Any collection, translation or interpretations of foreign news media coverage (including but not limited to Georgian and Russian language media) about the political ramifications of Nixon's visit to Georgia on March 31st of 1991. 

Any agency documents which might be understood to be a "narrative" of the visit or a written documentation of Nixon's itinerary as recorded by an agency employee or source. 

Any agency documents which might be understood to be a "narrative" of the visit or a written documentation of Nixon's itinerary from any source, currently maintained in the agency's records. 

The FOIA act provides that if portions of a document are exempt from release, the remainder must be segregated and disclosed. Therefore, I will expect you to send all nonexempt portions of the records which I have requested, and ask that you justify any deletions be referencing the specific provisions of the FOI act used to justify the deletions.

Thank you for your commitment to transparency, and I look forward to continue working on this request. This granting of this request would have significant historical value for both the United States and Georgia.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robert Delaware
